Tests that ALTER TABLE ... PARTITIONED BY NONE (partition collapse) resumes
correctly after the master is killed mid-way through the schema change.

Scenario 1 — basic collapse resume:
  Partition a fresh table with 3 shards, populate, collapse with scdelay,
  kill master, restart, verify all rows present and no partition metadata.

Scenario 2 — collapse resume after a prior ALTER TABLE:
  Before collapsing, run an ALTER TABLE that completes (which sets db->plan
  to NULL via sc_alter_table.c:1116 after promotion). Then collapse with a
  kill mid-way. Tests the USE_NEWDB_FOR_SC_GENIDS fix: without it,
  is_dta_being_rebuilt(db->plan=NULL) always returns false, causing resume
  to read sc_genids from llmeta even when they are stored in the new btree,
  resulting in genid=0 for all stripes and duplicate-key errors on restart.

Scenario 3 — two concurrent partition collapses of different kinds, resume:
  Launches two simultaneous collapses in the background:
    t3: created by "CREATE TABLE ... PARTITIONED BY TIME" (non-aliased,
        first shard is a separate $0_XXXX table; collapse creates a new
        target table and moves all shard rows into it).
    t4: created by "CREATE TABLE + ALTER TABLE ... PARTITIONED BY TIME"
        (aliased, the original table is shard 0; collapse reuses it as the
        target and moves remaining shards into it).
  Both are killed mid-way through the first shard.  On restart each gets its
  own scl entry and its own _partitioned_table_merge_resume_thd thread, which
  run concurrently on the same iq — the scenario the sc_pending_mtx race fix
  (commit 572faf76e) protects.  This exercises the logic that iterates over
  multiple partition schema changes across concurrent resume threads.

Scenario 4 — transactional multi-DDL partition collapse, resume:
  Sends BEGIN; ALTER TABLE t5 PARTITIONED BY NONE; ALTER TABLE t6 PARTITIONED
  BY NONE; COMMIT as four separate cdb2sql calls.  The first three return
  immediately (cdb2api line-6391 optimization for non-read in-transaction
  statements).  The final "commit" blocks (is_commit=1) waiting for the server
  to finish bplog_schemachange.  Master is killed during the blocking commit.
  On restart the new master finds scl entries for both tables in llmeta and
  resumes both collapses.  This tests the transactional DDL resume path
  (bplog_schemachange → resume_sc_multiddl_txn) as opposed to the standalone
  concurrent collapse path tested in scenario 3.
